children.subject: Someone should just make a cumulative post for "should I take xx before yy" at this point :P

Thx! Is there any information about the STAT course? I saw on Facebook that it has overlap with CS 189, but I would like to know whether taking it before 189 helps, or EECS 127 is a much better choice.

Stat 151A has some overlap with 189 (OLS, Ridge and Lasso Regression, and Logistic Regression), but 151A focuses more on the theory behind different regression models and what we should do when these assumptions are not true. On the other hand, when I took 189 (I do not know if this is the case with Professor Sahai's version), we kind of just assumed that the assumptions for these models hold true and covered a broad more number of topics that 151A does not cover (I think we covered all of the overlap in the first two weeks of class in 189?). I do not think 151A will help much with 189, but it's a worthwhile class on its own right due to the fact that linear models will always be what statisticians and economists will turn to first.

history.content:
Yes, there is a lot of overlap, though 126 is more important. 127 can be done concurrently

======= 

I think 127 is much more important, although of course this is subjective. All you really need from 126 is an understanding of Gaussian random variables - things like multi-variate Gaussians are introduced in the class - whereas a solid grasp of optimization will help you understand 60-80% of the material.
Yes, there is a lot of overlap, though 126 is more important. 127 can be done concurrently

Does taking EECS 127 before CS 189 helps a lot?

P.S. can anyone who has taken STAT 151A comment on whether it's helpful for CS 189? I've heard it's also a linear algebra heavy course. I've taken STAT 134 and 135.
